{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox artist | name = Roland Poska | image = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1938 | birth_place = Scotland | death_date = February 2, {{death year and age|2017|1938}} | death_place = [[Rockford, Illinois]], US | nationality = American | movement = | awards = | elected = | patrons = | website = {{url|http://rolandposka.com}} | field = {{hlist|[[Printmaking]]|[[papermaking]]|[[painting]]}} | training = {{hlist|[[Rockford College]]|[[Cranbrook Educational Community|Cranbrook Academy of Art]]}} | works = {{ubl|"The Great Human Race"|"From Blue to Blue"}} }}
'''Roland Poska''' (1938 – February 2, 2017) was an American artist who was notable for pioneering [[papermaking]] in modern art,<ref name="rrs">{{cite news|url=http://www.rrstar.com/news/20170206/stupid-man-kicks-bucket?template=printart|title='Stupid' man kicks the bucket|last=Haas|first=Kevin|date=February 6, 2017|work=Rockford Star|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> for [[printmaking]], and for frequently combining the two into completed works of art. He was also a teacher at the [[Layton School of Art]] in [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]], a co-founder of the [[Milwaukee Institute of Art & Design]], and founder of the lithography studio the Fishy Whale Press.
==Biography== Poska was born to Lithuanian parents in Scotland in 1938. At age 10, he and his parents immigrated to the United States, and settled in [[Rockford, Illinois]].<ref name="RRT">{{cite news|url=http://rockrivertimes.com/wpapp/vibe-entertainment/2010/09/22/ethnic-heritage-museum%E2%80%99s-polish-gallery-profiles-roland-poska/|title=Ethnic Heritage Museum’s Polish Gallery profiles Roland Poska|date=September 22–28, 2010|work=The Rock River Times|accessdate=August 22, 2017|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170822095312/http://rockrivertimes.com/wpapp/vibe-entertainment/2010/09/22/ethnic-heritage-museum%E2%80%99s-polish-gallery-profiles-roland-poska/|archivedate=August 22, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> After receiving degrees from [[Rockford College]] and [[Cranbrook Educational Community|Cranbrook Academy of Art]], he became an instructor at Rockford College, then in 1963, moved to Milwaukee, where he taught at the [[Layton School of Art]].<ref name="Lituanus">{{cite journal|last=Gilman|first=Mack|date=Winter 1987|title=Roland Poska|journal=Lituanus|publisher=LITUANUS Foundation, Inc.|volume= 33|issue=4|issn=0024-5089}}</ref> When Layton closed, he co-founded the Milwaukee School of Art and Design and taught there.<ref name="rrs"/>
In 1963, while attending Cranbrook, Poska was introduced to papermaking by [[Laurence Barker]], the dean of the school's graphics department.<ref name="ce">{{cite book|title=The Cutting Edge: New Directions in Handmade Paper|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EI5PAAAAMAAJ&q=roland+poska&dq=roland+poska&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJu_7G6OnVAhUL7oMKHZANDf0Q6AEILDAB|year=1988|publisher=The Institute|isbn=0933742142}}</ref> In 1967, he purchased his first "beater", a machine that grinds rags and pulp in the initial step of producing handmade paper, and established his lithography studio the Fishy Whale Press.<ref name="Lituanus"/> At the time, his lithography press was among the largest in the United States, using {{convert|600|lb}} blocks of stone. Under the Fishy Whale imprint, Poska and artist John Doyle produced ''The Great Human Race'', a series of prints designed by Doyle that appear in the collections of a number of American museums.<ref name="Lituanus"/> Poska continued to develop ''The Great Human Race'' as a perpetual art and philosophy project for over 30 years.<ref name="JRK">{{cite web|url=http://jrkortman.com/the-art-of-roland-poska-and-music-from-keith|title=The art of Roland Poska and music from Keith Grace's iPod this First Friday @ J.R. Kortman|date=March 29, 2011|work=JRKortman|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> He would go on to be recognized as a pioneer in the artistic medium of papermaking.<ref name="BCA">{{cite web|url=http://centerforbookarts.org/collections-spotlight-north-american-hand-papermaking-1976-richard-minsky-et-al/|title=Collections Spotlight: North American Hand Papermaking 1976, Richard Minsky, et al.|work=The Center For Book Arts|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>
By 1984, Poska was a nationally known artist.<ref name="TT">{{cite news|url=http://www.mywebtimes.com/news/illinois_ap/rockford-artist-envisions-day-without-prejudice/article_deb85984-70a9-57d6-92ce-f49978e1d9c1.html|title=Rockford artist envisions day without prejudice|last=Associated Press|date=July 28, 2010|work=The Times|accessdate=August 26, 2017}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> That year, he received a commission to produce a {{convert|270|ft|adj=on}} long painting ''From Blue to Blue'', which was displayed on Main Street in Rockford<ref name="TT"/> before its installation in Milwaukee's [[Henry S. Reuss]] Federal Plaza Building. This piece was produced in sections {{convert|6|to|8|ft}} high and {{convert|12|to|16|ft}} long, and then assembled to complete the full installation.<ref name="Lituanus"/>
His works are included in the collections of the [[Art Institute of Chicago]]<ref name="AIC">{{cite web|url=http://www.artic.edu/aic/collections/artwork/artist/Poska%2C+Roland|title=Poska, Roland The Art Institute of Chicago|work=The Art Institute of Chicago|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> and [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]].<ref name="MET">{{cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/661944|title=Prints of the Fishy Whale|work=The Metropolitan Museum of Art|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref>
In his later years, Poska became an outspoken activist for equality and common human rights,<ref name="rrs"/> and was a frequent speaker at Rockford town hall meetings.<ref name="rrs2">{{cite news|url=http://www.rrstar.com/news/20160815/man-banned-from-rockford-city-hall-for-one-month-after-golf-club-incident|title=Man banned from Rockford City Hall for one month after golf club incident|last=Haas|first=Kevin|date=August 15, 2016|work=Rockford Star|accessdate=August 22, 2017}}</ref> He died on February 2, 2017, in Rockford.<ref name="rrs" />
==References== {{Reflist|30em}}
{{Authority control}}
{{DEFAULTSORT:Poska, Roland}} [[Category:1938 births]] [[Category:2017 deaths]] [[Category:20th-century American painters]] [[Category:21st-century American painters]] [[Category:20th-century American printmakers]] [[Category:21st-century American printmakers]] [[Category:American male painters]] [[Category:Artists from Milwaukee]] [[Category:Artists from Illinois]] [[Category:Papermakers]] [[Category:American contemporary artists]] [[Category:Art educators]] [[Category:Cranbrook Academy of Art alumni]] [[Category:Rockford University alumni]] [[Category:American people of Lithuanian descent]]

A '''''répétiteur''''' (from [[French language|French]] [[verb]] ''répéter'' meaning "to repeat, to go over, to learn, to [[rehearsal|rehearse]]"<ref name=oed/>) is an accompanist, tutor or coach of ballet dancers or opera dancers.

== Opera ==
In [[opera]], a ''répétiteur'' is the person responsible for coaching singers and playing the [[piano]] for music and production rehearsals.<ref name=oed>[http://dictionary.oed.com/cgi/entry/50203075?single=1&query_type=word&queryword=repetiteur&first=1&max_to_show=10 Oxford English Dictionary], Oxford University Press, accessed 27 July 2010 {{subscription}}</ref> When coaching solo singers or choir members, the ''répétiteur'' will take on a number of the roles of a [[vocal coach]]: advising singers on how to improve their pitch and pronunciation, and correcting note or phrasing errors.

''Répétiteurs'' are skilled musicians who have strong [[sight-reading]] and score reading skills. In addition to being able to sight read piano parts, a ''répétiteur'' can play on the piano an orchestral score reducing it in real-time ([[orchestral reduction]]), by reading from a large open score of all of the instruments and voice parts. ''Répétiteurs'' are also skilled in following the directions of a conductor, in terms of changing the tempo, pausing, or adding other nuances.

== Ballet ==
In [[ballet]], a ''répétiteur'' teaches the steps and interpretation of the roles to some or all of the company performing a dance.<ref name=oed/> Several late 20th-century choreographers, such as [[George Balanchine#External links|George Balanchine]], [[Jerome Robbins#External links|Jerome Robbins]] and [[Twyla Tharp]], have established trusts and appointed conservators—hand-picked dancers who have intimate knowledge of particular ballets—as ''répétiteurs'' of their works.

